and nam (N) in some old texts.) In Irish manuscripts, Dr Traube had noted N only in

Diarmaid's Latin commentary on Theodorus of Mopsuestia in the Ambrosian Library (c. 301 inf.). He suggests that further search would probably lead to the discovery of other examples; but considers these sufficient fully to confirm my view that the symbol in Vat. reg. lat. 81 represents nam.

Perhaps someone who sees more early manuscripts than I can hope to see will find instances in which the same form of N is used with the same stroke through the second limb.
